The problem C-I-C-D solves on Databricks.

To see why bundles exist, look at what promoting a pipeline from dev to prod used to mean. You really had two options, and both were bad.

Option A was point-and-click. Engineers cloned notebooks across workspaces by hand, copy-pasted job J-S-O-N, and updated paths manually. Drift was inevitable — prod ended up running a job spec slightly different from dev, and over months the two quietly diverged.

Option B was R-E-S-T A-P-I scripts. Teams wrote bash that called the Jobs A-P-I and the Workspace A-P-I to upload notebooks and create jobs. That's workable, but every team reinvented the same plumbing in a slightly different way. There was just no canonical way to say "this pipeline, plus this job, plus these notebooks, deployed together as one unit."

Automation Bundles solve exactly that. You get a single declarative file — databricks-dot-y-m-l — that describes every resource in your project, and a C-L-I that validates, deploys, and runs that bundle against any target workspace. The same source tree promotes from dev, to test, to prod, by changing one C-L-I flag. That's the whole idea.

Our worked example for the module is the bank's fintech-platform Git repo. It holds the ingestion, silver, and gold notebooks, the declarative pipeline from module five, the nightly job from module six, and one databricks-dot-y-m-l that promotes the whole bundle across three workspaces.

And here's the exam's framing to recognise. When a question says "a team needs a modular, version-controlled way to deploy and orchestrate E-T-L, with C-I-C-D and repeatability," the answer is Automation Bundles in Git, deployed with bundle-deploy. It is never hand-cloning notebooks, and never snapshotting the U-I.
